00030 /* Threaded node structure */
00031 struct tbbt_node
00032   {
00033       VOIDP       data;         /* Pointer to user data to be associated with node */
00034       VOIDP       key;          /* Field to sort nodes on */
00035 
00036 #ifdef TBBT_INTERNALS
00037 # define   PARENT  0
00038 # define   LEFT    1
00039 # define   RIGHT   2
00040       TBBT_NODE  *link[3];      /* Pointers to parent, left child, and right child */
00041 # define  Parent    link[PARENT]
00042 # define  Lchild    link[LEFT]
00043 # define  Rchild    link[RIGHT]
00044 # define  TBBT_FLAG unsigned long
00045 # define  TBBT_LEAF unsigned long
00046       TBBT_FLAG   flags;        /* Combination of the following bit fields: */
00047 # define  TBBT_HEAVY(s) s       /* If the `s' sub-tree is deeper than the other */
00048 # define  TBBT_DOUBLE   4       /* If "heavy" sub-tree is two levels deeper */
00049 # define  TBBT_INTERN   8       /* If node is internal (has two children) */
00050 # define  TBBT_UNBAL    ( TBBT_HEAVY(LEFT) | TBBT_HEAVY(RIGHT) )
00051 # define  TBBT_FLAGS    ( TBBT_UNBAL | TBBT_INTERN | TBBT_DOUBLE )
00052 # define  TBBT_CHILD(s) ( TBBT_INTERN | TBBT_HEAVY(s) )
00053       TBBT_LEAF   lcnt;         /* count of left children */
00054       TBBT_LEAF   rcnt;         /* count of right children */
00055 # define  LeftCnt(node) ( (node)->lcnt )    /* Left descendants */
00056 # define  RightCnt(node) ( (node)->rcnt )   /* Left descendants */
00057 #if defined macintosh || defined MAC || defined SYMANTEC_C     /* Macro substitution limit */
00058 # define  Cnt(node,s)   ( 1==(s) ? LeftCnt(node) : RightCnt(node) )
00059 #else                           /* !macintosh */
00060 # define  Cnt(node,s)   ( LEFT==(s) ? LeftCnt(node) : RightCnt(node) )
00061 #endif                          /* !macintosh */
00062 # define  HasChild(n,s) ( Cnt(n,s)>0 )
00063 # define  Heavy(n,s)    ( (s) & (LeftCnt(n)>RightCnt(n) ? LEFT : \
00064                  LeftCnt(n)==RightCnt(n) ? 0 : RIGHT))
00065 # define  Intern(n)     ( LeftCnt(n) && RightCnt(n) )
00066 # define  UnBal(n)      ( LeftCnt(n)>RightCnt(n) ? LEFT : \
00067                  LeftCnt(n)==RightCnt(n) ? 0 : RIGHT)
00068 # define  Double(n)     ( TBBT_DOUBLE & (n)->flags )
00069 # define  Other(side)   ( LEFT + RIGHT - (side) )
00070 # define  Delta(n,s)    (  ( Heavy(n,s) ? 1 : -1 )                          \
00071                             *  ( Double(n) ? 2 : UnBal(n) ? 1 : 0 )  )
00072 # define  SetFlags(n,s,b,i)   (  ( -2<(b) && (b)<2 ? 0 : TBBT_DOUBLE )   \
00073     |  ( 0>(b) ? TBBT_HEAVY(s) : (b)>0 ? TBBT_HEAVY(Other(s)) : 0 )        \
00074     |  ( (i) ? TBBT_INTERN : 0 )  )
00075   };

00103 /* These routines are designed to allow use of a general-purpose balanced tree
00104  * implimentation.  These trees are appropriate for maintaining in memory one
00105  * or more lists of items, each list sorted according to key values (key values
00106  * must form a "completely ordered set") where no two items in a single list
00107  * can have the same key value.  The following operations are supported:
00108  *     Create an empty list
00109  *     Add an item to a list
00110  *     Look up an item in a list by key value
00111  *     Look up the Nth item in a list
00112  *     Delete an item from a list
00113  *     Find the first/last/next/previous item in a list
00114  *     Destroy a list
00115  * Each of the above operations requires Order(log(N)) time where N is the
00116  * number of items in the list (except for list creation which requires
00117  * constant time and list destruction which requires Order(N) time if the user-
00118  * supplied free-data-item or free-key-value routines require constant time).
00119  * Each of the above operations (except create and destroy) can be performed
00120  * on a subtree.
00121  *
00122  * Each node of a tree has associated with it a generic pointer (void *) which
00123  * is set to point to one such "item" and a generic pointer to point to that
00124  * item's "key value".  The structure of the items and key values is up to the
00125  * user to define.  The user must specify a method for comparing key values.
00126  * This routine takes three arguments, two pointers to key values and a third
00127  * integer argument.  You can specify a routine that expects pointers to "data
00128  * items" rather than key values in which case the pointer to the key value in
00129  * each node will be set equal to the pointer to the data item.
00130  *
00131  * Since the "data item" pointer is the first field of each tree node, these
00132  * routines may be used without this "tbbt.h" file.  For example, assume "ITM"
00133  * is the structre definition for the data items you want to store in lists:
00134  * ITM ***tbbtdmake( int (*cmp)(void *,void *,int), int arg );
00135  * ITM **root= NULL;        (* How to create an empty tree w/o tbbtdmake() *)
00136  * ITM **tbbtdfind( ITM ***tree, void *key, ITM ***pp );
00137  * ITM **tbbtfind( ITM **root, void *key, int (*cmp)(), int arg, ITM ***pp );
00138  * ITM **tbbtdless( ITM ***tree, void *key, ITM ***pp );
00139  * ITM **tbbtless( ITM **root, void *key, int (*cmp)(), int arg, ITM ***pp );
00140  * ITM **tbbtindx( ITM **root, long indx );
00141  * ITM **tbbtdins( ITM ***tree, ITM *item, void *key );
00142  * ITM **tbbtins( ITM ***root, ITM *item, void *key, int (*cmp)(), int arg );
00143  * ITM *tbbtrem( ITM ***root, ITM **node, void **kp );
00144  * ITM **tbbtfirst( ITM **root ), **tbbtlast( ITM **root );
00145  * ITM **tbbtnext( ITM **node ), **tbbtprev( ITM **node );
00146  * ITM ***tbbtdfree( ITM ***tree, void (*df)(ITM *), void (*kf)(void *) );
00147  * void tbbtfree( ITM ***root, void (*df)(ITM *), void (*kf)(void *) );
00148  */
00149

00155 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_TREE  *tbbtdmake
00156                 (intn (*compar) (VOIDP, VOIDP, intn), intn arg, uintn fast_compare);
00157 /* Allocates and initializes an empty threaded, balanced, binary tree and
00158  * returns a pointer to the control structure for it.  You can also create
00159  * empty trees without this function as long as you never use tbbtd* routines
00160  * (tbbtdfind, tbbtdins, tbbtdfree) on them.
00161  * Examples:
00162  *     int keycmp();
00163  *     TBBT_ROOT *root= tbbtdmake( keycmp, (int)keysiz , 0);
00164  * or
00165  *     void *root= tbbtdmake( strcmp, 0 , 0);
00166  * or
00167  *     void *root= tbbtdmake( keycmp, (int)keysiz , TBBT_FAST_UINT16_COMPARE);
00168  * or
00169  *     TBBT_NODE *root= NULL;        (* Don't use tbbtd* routines *)
00170  * `cmp' is the routine to be used to compare two key values [in tbbtdfind()
00171  * and tbbtdins()].  The arguments to `cmp' are the two keys to compare
00172  * and `arg':  (*cmp)(k1,k2,arg).  `cmp' is expected to return 0 if its first
00173  * two arguments point to identical key values, -1 (or any integer less than 0)
00174  * if k1 points to a key value lower than that pointed to by k2, and 1 (or any
00175  * integer greater than 0) otherwise.  If `cmp' is NULL, memcmp is used.  If
00176  * `cmp' is NULL and `arg' is not greater than 0L, `1+strlen(key1)' is used in
00177  * place of `arg' to emulate strcmp():  memcmp( k1, k2, 1+strlen(k1) ).  You
00178  * can use strcmp() directly (as in the second example above) as long as your C
00179  * compiler does not assume strcmp() will always be passed exactly 2 arguments
00180  * (only newer, ANSI-influenced C compilers are likely to be able to make this
00181  * kind of assumption).  You can also use a key comparison routine that expects
00182  * pointers to data items rather than key values.
00183  *  The "fast compare" option is for keys of simple numeric types (currently
00184  *      uint16 and int32) and avoids the function call for faster searches in
00185  *      some cases.  The key comparison routine is still required for some
00186  *      insertion routines which use it.
00187  *
00188  * Most of the other routines expect a pointer to a root node of a tree, not
00189  * a pointer to the tree's control structure (only tbbtdfind(), tbbtdins(),
00190  * and tbbtdfree() expect pointers to control structures).  However TBBT_TREE
00191  * is just defined as "**TBBT_NODE" (unless you have defined TBBT_INTERNALS so
00192  * you have access to the internal structure of the nodes) so
00193  *     TBBT_TREE *tree1= tbbtdmake( NULL, 0 );
00194  * is equivalent to
00195  *     TBBT_NODE **tree1= tbbtdmake( NULL, 0 );
00196  * So could be used as:
00197  *     node= tbbtdfind( tree1, key, NULL );
00198  *     node= tbbtfind( *tree1, key, compar, arg, NULL );
00199  *     node= tbbtdless( tree1, key, NULL );
00200  *     node= tbbtless( *tree1, key, compar, arg, NULL );
00201  *     node= tbbtdins( tree1, item, key );
00202  *     node= tbbtins( tree1, item, key, compar, arg );
00203  *     item= tbbtrem( tree1, tbbtdfind(tree1,key,NULL), NULL );
00204  *     item= tbbtrem( tree1, tbbtfind(*tree1,key,compar,arg,NULL), NULL );
00205  *     tree1= tbbtdfree( tree1, free, NULL );       (* or whatever *)
00206  * while
00207  *     TBBT_NODE *root= NULL;
00208  * would be used like:
00209  *     node= tbbtfind( root, key );
00210  *     node= tbbtins( &root, item, key );
00211  *     node= tbbtrem( &root, tbbtfind(root,key), NULL );
00212  *     tbbtfree( &root, free, NULL );               (* or whatever *)
00213  * Never use tbbtfree() on a tree allocated with tbbtdmake() or on a sub-tree
00214  * of ANY tree.  Never use tbbtdfree() except on a tbbtdmake()d tree.
00215  */
00216 
00217 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtdfind
00218                 (TBBT_TREE * tree, VOIDP key, TBBT_NODE ** pp);
00219 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtfind
00220                 (TBBT_NODE * root, VOIDP key, intn (*cmp) (VOIDP, VOIDP, intn),
00221                  intn arg, TBBT_NODE ** pp);
00222 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtdless
00223                 (TBBT_TREE * tree, VOIDP key, TBBT_NODE ** pp);
00224 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtless
00225                 (TBBT_NODE * root, VOIDP key, intn (*cmp) (VOIDP, VOIDP, intn),
00226                  intn arg, TBBT_NODE ** pp);
00227 /* Locate a node based on the key given.  A pointer to the node in the tree
00228  * with a key value matching `key' is returned.  If no such node exists, NULL
00229  * is returned.  Whether a node is found or not, if `pp' is not NULL, `*pp'
00230  * will be set to point to the parent of the node we are looking for (or that
00231  * node that would be the parent if the node is not found).  tbbtdfind() is
00232  * used on trees created using tbbtdmake() (so that `cmp' and `arg' don't have
00233  * to be passed).  tbbtfind() can be used on the root or any subtree of a tree
00234  * create using tbbtdmake() and is used on any tree (or subtree) created with-
00235  * out using tbbtdmake().  tbbtless() & tbbtdless() work exactly like tbbtfind()
00236  * and tbbtdfind() except that they find the node with a key which is less than
00237  * or equal to the key given to them.
00238  */
00239 
00240 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtindx
00241                 (TBBT_NODE * root, int32 indx);
00242 /* Locate the node that has `indx' nodes with lesser key values.  This is like
00243  * an array lookup with the first item in the list having index 0.  For large
00244  * values of `indx', this call is much faster than tbbtfirst() followed by
00245  * `indx' tbbtnext()s.  Thus `tbbtindx(&root,0L)' is equivalent to (and almost
00246  * as fast as) `tbbtfirst(root)'.
00247  */
00248 
00249 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtdins
00250                 (TBBT_TREE * tree, VOIDP item, VOIDP key);
00251 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtins
00252                 (TBBT_NODE ** root, VOIDP item, VOIDP key, intn (*cmp) (VOIDP, VOIDP, intn), intn arg);
00253 /* Insert a new node to the tree having a key value of `key' and a data pointer
00254  * of `item'.  If a node already exists in the tree with key value `key' or if
00255  * malloc() fails, NULL is returned (no node is inserted), otherwise a pointer
00256  * to the inserted node is returned.  `cmp' and `arg' are as for tbbtfind().
00257  */
00258 
00259 HDFLIBAPI VOIDP       tbbtrem
00260                 (TBBT_NODE ** root, TBBT_NODE * node, VOIDP *kp);
00261 /* Remove the node pointed to by `node' from the tree with root `root'.  The
00262  * data pointer for the deleted node is returned.  If the second argument is
00263  * NULL, NULL is returned.  If `kp' is not NULL, `*kp' is set to point to the
00264  * key value for the deleted node.  Examples:
00265  *     data= tbbtrem( tree, tbbtdfind(tree,key), &kp );  free(data);  free(kp);
00266  *     data= tbbtrem( &root, tbbtfind(root,key,compar,arg), NULL );
00267  *     data= tbbtrem( &tree->root, tbbtdfind(tree,key), NULL );
00268  */

00272 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_NODE  *tbbtlast
00273                 (TBBT_NODE * root);
00274 /* Returns a pointer to node from the tree with the lowest(first)/highest(last)
00275  * key value.  If the tree is empy NULL is returned.  Examples:
00276  *     node= tbbtfirst(*tree);
00277  *     node= tbbtfirst(root);
00278  *     node= tbbtlast(tree->root);
00279  *     node= tbbtlast(node);        (* Last node in a sub-tree *)
00280  */

00286 /* Returns a pointer the node from the tree with the next highest (previous
00287  * lowest) key value relative to the node pointed to by `node'.  If `node'
00288  * points the last (first) node of the tree, NULL is returned.

00291 HDFLIBAPI TBBT_TREE  *tbbtdfree
00292                 (TBBT_TREE * tree, VOID(*fd) (VOIDP), VOID(*fk) (VOIDP));
00293 HDFLIBAPI VOID        tbbtfree
00294                 (TBBT_NODE ** root, VOID(*fd) (VOIDP), VOID(*fk) (VOIDP));
00295 /* Frees up an entire tree.  `fd' is a pointer to a function that frees/
00296  * destroys data items, and `fk' is the same for key values.
00297  *     void free();
00298  *       tree= tbbtdfree( tree, free, free );
00299  *       tbbtfree( &root, free, free );
00300  * is a typical usage, where keys and data are individually malloc()d.  If `fk'
00301  * is NULL, no action is done for the key values (they were allocated on the
00302  * stack, as a part of each data item, or together with one malloc() call, for
00303  * example) and likewise for `fd'.  tbbtdfree() always returns NULL and
00304  * tbbtfree() always sets `root' to be NULL.
00305  */
00306
